<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="394" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1099,2026]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1136,1162]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Etymology.</emphasis>
The genus name is a combination of the Latin prefix “ 
<emphasis box="[944,1016,1135,1161]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Salsus</emphasis>
” meaning salty combined with genus name “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Guerin-Meneville" authorityYear="1830" box="[231,293,1172,1197]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Laius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="394" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[231,293,1172,1197]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Laius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, referring to the unusual habitat of this new genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="394" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1099,2026]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1207,1233]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This genus can be easily recognized from the all other genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mulsant &amp; Rey" authorityYear="1867" box="[1055,1189,1207,1233]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Apalochrini">Apalochrini</taxonomicName>
by biserrate antennae in both male and female, highly reduced vesicles on thorax and abdomen and distinctly exposed pygidium from above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="396" pageId="1" pageNumber="394" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1099,2026]" box="[199,1401,1315,1342]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1315,1341]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Description.</emphasis>
Body (
<figureCitation box="[427,567,1315,1342]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[178,1404,468,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-155@2.[165,1422,453,1958]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov. (A–D) holotype, male: (A) dorsal view; (B) ventral view; (C) lateral view; (D) head, frontal view. (E–G) paratype, female: (E) dorsal view; (F) head, frontal view; (G) ventral view. Scale bars 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792841/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs 1A–1G</figureCitation>
) relatively flattened, nearly parallel-sided; vestiture of short whitish setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1099,2026]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,263,1352,1378]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Head</emphasis>
prognathous; median occipital carina present, extending to middle of frons (
<figureCitation box="[1126,1265,1351,1378]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[178,1404,468,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-155@2.[165,1422,453,1958]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov. (A–D) holotype, male: (A) dorsal view; (B) ventral view; (C) lateral view; (D) head, frontal view. (E–G) paratype, female: (E) dorsal view; (F) head, frontal view; (G) ventral view. Scale bars 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792841/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs 1A, 1E</figureCitation>
); frons slightly depressed anteriorly, with pair of small pits (
<figureCitation box="[635,768,1387,1414]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[178,1404,468,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-155@2.[165,1422,453,1958]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov. (A–D) holotype, male: (A) dorsal view; (B) ventral view; (C) lateral view; (D) head, frontal view. (E–G) paratype, female: (E) dorsal view; (F) head, frontal view; (G) ventral view. Scale bars 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792841/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs 1D, 1F</figureCitation>
). Eyes medium-sized, finely facetted and slightly protruding. Antennae dorsally and anteriorly inserted on frons. Clypeus of very short sclerotized postclypeus and trapezoid membranous anteclypeus. Labrum transverse and sub-rectangular. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[942,1029,1459,1486]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,224,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[151,1435,211,1526]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov., paratype, male: (A) antenna, dorsal; (B) maxilla, ventral; (C) labium, ventral; (D) mandible, ventral; (E) fore tarsi; (F) tergite VIII; (G) sternite VIII; (H) genitalia; (I) spicular gastrum. Scale bars 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792845/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
) 11-segmented, scape elongated and subtriangular, pedicel very short and almost invisible; antennomere 3–11 asymmetrically biserrate and densely covered by short sensorial setae, antennomere 3 elongated. Mandibles (
<figureCitation box="[840,926,1531,1558]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,224,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[151,1435,211,1526]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov., paratype, male: (A) antenna, dorsal; (B) maxilla, ventral; (C) labium, ventral; (D) mandible, ventral; (E) fore tarsi; (F) tergite VIII; (G) sternite VIII; (H) genitalia; (I) spicular gastrum. Scale bars 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792845/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
) bidentate apically, incisor edge smooth; mola absent, of membranous appendages. Maxilla (
<figureCitation box="[653,737,1567,1594]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,224,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[151,1435,211,1526]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov., paratype, male: (A) antenna, dorsal; (B) maxilla, ventral; (C) labium, ventral; (D) mandible, ventral; (E) fore tarsi; (F) tergite VIII; (G) sternite VIII; (H) genitalia; (I) spicular gastrum. Scale bars 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792845/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
) with slender palps, terminal palpomere elongated and cylindrical; galea and lacinia subequal in length, covered by dense short setae anteriorly. Labium (
<figureCitation box="[1141,1225,1603,1630]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,224,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[151,1435,211,1526]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov., paratype, male: (A) antenna, dorsal; (B) maxilla, ventral; (C) labium, ventral; (D) mandible, ventral; (E) fore tarsi; (F) tergite VIII; (G) sternite VIII; (H) genitalia; (I) spicular gastrum. Scale bars 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792845/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
) with 3-segmented labial palps, terminal palpomere conical; ligula rounded apically. Gular sutures short and widely separated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1099,2026]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1676,1702]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Prothorax</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[336,471,1675,1702]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[178,1404,468,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-155@2.[165,1422,453,1958]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov. (A–D) holotype, male: (A) dorsal view; (B) ventral view; (C) lateral view; (D) head, frontal view. (E–G) paratype, female: (E) dorsal view; (F) head, frontal view; (G) ventral view. Scale bars 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792841/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs 1A, 1E</figureCitation>
) weakly transverse; anterior side pronounced in the middle and slightly hollowed near anterior angles, so the angles look acute and slightly prominent. lateral and posterior edges slightly expanded, with narrow and transparent flanges; dorsal surface slightly convex, covered by dense and short whitish setae. Prosternum very short, prosternal process highly reduced. Procoxal cavities contiguous; procoxae large and distinctly projecting, protrochantins exposed. Vesicles pale yellow. Scutellum sub-trapezoidal, with posterior margin rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1099,2026]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,151,429]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="395" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,275,1856,1882]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Elytra</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[290,425,1855,1882]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[178,1404,468,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-155@2.[165,1422,453,1958]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov. (A–D) holotype, male: (A) dorsal view; (B) ventral view; (C) lateral view; (D) head, frontal view. (E–G) paratype, female: (E) dorsal view; (F) head, frontal view; (G) ventral view. Scale bars 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792841/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs 1A, 1E</figureCitation>
) nearly parallel-sided, rounded apically, lateral margins slightly constricted at about apical third, inner suture marginated and elevate, each elytron with two weak longitudinal carinae, parallel to suture; dorsal surfaces without distinct punctuation, covered by dense and short yellowish setae. Hindwings well developed. Mesoventrite and mesanepisternum fused and transverse, mesepimeron sub-triangular, yellow with black-brown anterior side (
<figureCitation box="[308,450,1999,2026]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[178,1404,468,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-155@2.[165,1422,453,1958]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov. (A–D) holotype, male: (A) dorsal view; (B) ventral view; (C) lateral view; (D) head, frontal view. (E–G) paratype, female: (E) dorsal view; (F) head, frontal view; (G) ventral view. Scale bars 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792841/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs 1B, 1G</figureCitation>
). Mesocoxal cavities contiguous, laterally open to mesepimeron; mesocoxae elongated and large, mesotrochantins exposed. Metaventrite transverse and slightly swollen, discrimen complete; metanepisternum large and subtriangular, metepimeron exposed posteriorly from ventral side, not extending to lateral edge of metacoxae. Metacoxae large and sub-triangular, gradually narrowing to lateral. Legs with femora slightly enlarged, tibiae slender and slightly curved. Tarsal formula 5-5-5; fore tarsomere 2 (
<figureCitation box="[979,1063,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,224,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[151,1435,211,1526]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Salsolaius biserratus gen. et sp. nov., paratype, male: (A) antenna, dorsal; (B) maxilla, ventral; (C) labium, ventral; (D) mandible, ventral; (E) fore tarsi; (F) tergite VIII; (G) sternite VIII; (H) genitalia; (I) spicular gastrum. Scale bars 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792845/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
) in male strongly prolonged over next two segments, bearing black combs along apical and outer edges, tarsomeres 1 and 3 slightly elongate with the former segment slightly bilobed, tarsomere 4 shortened; mid and hind tarsi elongate, with basal 4 segments sub-equal in length, tarsomere 5 longest, claws long and thin, with small denticle at base; tarsomeres shortened and compact in female, with tarsomere 1 elongate, 2nd–4th tarsomeres compressed and equal in length, claws shorter.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5792841" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5792841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5792841/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="395" startId="2.[151,250,1981,2005]" targetBox="[178,1404,468,1943]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1981,2041]" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1981,2005]" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
